Ransomware is a malicious type of software that encrypts files or threatens to do so unless the user pays a certain amount usually in cryptocurrency such as Bitcoin for a "key" needed access their data backed up before getting infected, often exploiting human psychology and fear. Here're several ways how ransomware spread:

1. Phishing Emails/Messages - Most commonly via email attachments or malicious links lured into the systems which seem to come from legitimate sources e.g., banks, known colleagues etc; these messages usually contain misleading subjects like 'Urgent Salary Check' and promise exciting offers just enough to draw attention away from suspicious activity without raising alarms about security risks or data being sent out unethically into external storage devices/servers.

2. Malvertising (Malware advertisements) - A similar approach as phishing emails where ads are laced with exploits that when clicked on, can install ransomwares maliciously onto the system of their own or unwitting targets by masquerading amongst legitimate online content i.e., an extension being downloaded while viewing regular site search results could contain hidden code-infected .exe/s (launcher) scripts waiting to take offensive actions after installations complete successfully without realizing it until late detection processes have passed point of origin unreachable remotely by users themselves;

3. Exploited Vulnerabilities - Known as drive-by downloading attacks on poorly updated systems or outdated browsers etc since attackers can inject their ransomware directly onto a visitor's device when they visit compromised legitimate websites that contain exploit code, without ever having to interact/engage through human error.
    * Exploited Vulnerabilities (Exploit kits)- Using pre-developed hacking tools called "exploit kits" which are malicious scripts designed specifically with ransomware payloads in mind exploiting unpatched weaknesses on software applications/libraries installed across target computers allowing easy unauthorized access or execution while maintaining stealth till installation process being complete afterwards;
    * Compromised Websites - By compromising legitimate websites such as eCommerce platforms etc., they can inject malicious code that will infect systems automatically when someone visit their sites thus
